metadata.name: Algorithm, be my guide #147
metadata.description:
At length, I summoned the courage to approach.

-

I was worn. Months of aimless wandering have culminated in this series; a meditation on my struggles to find a direction in my life and with my art.

At times paralyzed by too many possibilities, and at other times completely void of ideas. I was lost in the depths of my thinking, overwhelmed by indecision and doubt.

Generative works are a form of process art, yet along the way I’d forgotten to “trust the process”. It was time to cede control and let each line of code light the way.

-

This project paints on a 2D canvas, pixel by pixel. I used a custom projection that blends isometric and perspective techniques, to create an uncanny viewpoint between the two. Objects are randomly generated, then an algorithm applies color mixing and position displacement to each pixel as it’s rendered.

By default the canvas has 2k pixels on its longest edge. You can change this in live view by pressing any number from 1-9. For example, pressing ‘4’ would render it with 4k pixels along the longest edge. I recommend ‘4’, but this can take up to a few minutes to render.

Press ‘s’ to save the rendered image.

metadata.name: Observance #6
metadata.description:
Happy birthday fxhash!

Observance is a collection of 365 pieces, one to mark each day of fxhash's first year.

4 seasons
7 days
12 months
365 dates

Each piece has an alternate birthday palette & all pieces can be saved as an SVG for plotting

Hit 'p' in live mode to save a 3720 × 5262px PNG
Hit 's' in live mode to save a plottable SVG

This is a generative NFT work by aotearoan, 2022

50% of proceeds go to support Processing.org

License: CC BY-NC-SA-4.0

metadata.name: Skravert #258
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: The Cosmic Soup #88
metadata.description:
The Cosmic Soup represents the early Universe shortly after the Big Bang. At this time, the Universe was extremely hot and energetic. As it expanded and cooled, the particles in the cosmic soup began to combine and form atoms, eventually giving rise to the first stars and galaxies.

The algorithm uses a combination of chaotic systems, geometry, and algebra to paint in real-time a representation of our Universe in the era when it was all one. Although most 20 color palettes have a dark background, others play with the algorithm's possibilities and represent space more abstractly.

Please read 'Dripping Pixels: Making "The Cosmic Soup"' for a complete explanation of this artwork's inspiration and creation.

The project is best viewed on a computer with good performance and in a high-resolution display.

- Press 'S' on the keyboard to save it as a PNG of 4096x2304 pixels or 5400x2304 pixels.
- Press 'F' on the keyboard to go full screen and restart the animation.
- Press 'R' on the keyboard to restart the animation.
- Press 'space' on the keyboard to pause the animation.

metadata.name: CHX-1 #197
metadata.description:
Glitching pixels like it’s 1999.

Inspired by 90’s digital aesthetics, CHX-1 takes a random selection of GAN seeds, combines them in unique ways, and processes them –individually and as a group– with a series of glitching dithering algorithms. Generating fun, original, colorful artworks. Millions of possibilities. Have fun!

<<< Base seeds generated offline using personal styleGAN2-ADA models. Image processing and combinations done generatively by the CHX-1 algorithm >>>

GAN –> p5js –> Blockchain


• Artworks can take a few seconds to load when running live code.

• Press “s” (when "open live" is active) to save a PNG image.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: EVENT HORIZON #18
metadata.description:
Depending on the mass of the black hole, ie its gravity, some (or all) stars will collide with it or will continue to move along elliptical orbits avoiding the event horizon.
Gravity will be turned off and on several times.
Drawing is finished after about 60 sec.

Press S to save png.

metadata.name: Atypical Lands #22
metadata.description:
The starting point of this project was to build something generative, but also connected. Each piece here is part of a world of its own, with several continents, seas, anomalies... Pieces from the same world can be assemble to build a larger map with varying colors, reliefs...
Terrains are build using noises and levelsets.

In its default version, the work is placed on a canvas. It is possible to press "F" to switch between the with or without canvas view. The "x" key allows to save a PNG of the current view. The "W" key allows to create a very high quality version of the piece. The piece is fully responsive.

There are about 60 palettes, the rarest versions being those with a light background (8%), transparent background (2%), and also when the painting is extended on the canvas (5%). 20 different worlds are possible, each with its own size (from 2x2 to 4x4).

Implemented by @Aqw_Zert with p5js

metadata.name: The Arcimboldo Project #69
metadata.description:
A tribute to Giuseppe Arcimboldo (1526 - 1593), an Italian painter best known for creating imaginative portrait heads made entirely of objects such as fruits, vegetables and flowers.

This token is made of a combination of 192 layers (24 layers x 8 fruits/vegetables/flowers categories).
All the layers have been hand-painted in acrylics on paper and digitally composed.
The background has a random HSV color.

As always a big thank you goes to Koei Ural - @KoeiUral for the huge help with the p5.js code!

metadata.name: Anagram #130
metadata.description:
'Anagram' explores the collision of nature with the modern world. Organic textures are generated within geometric boundaries to create a system of unique 'letters' that are combined and rearranged form a composition. Thirty-one texture types are possible, designed to work in five environments. Uncommon 'Assimilate' versions pull from the full texture set to represent the source 'word' of the generated Anagrams.

Artwork by 3dmanatee @3d_manatee. Made with p5js and ❤️.

metadata.name: orbitals #1
metadata.description:
In the year 2112 a new form of electromagnetic field is found to be produced by all known planets; these previously undiscovered fields seem to give rise to optimum orbital trajectories previously assumed to be impossible.

orbitals is a collection of 32 readouts from the Neumer Astro Plotter, tuned to detect and map these orbital EM fields on behalf of the Salfor Mining Company.

(made with P5.js)

metadata.name: Over the hills... #5
metadata.description:
A flurry of shapes, waves and colors at the intersection of figurative and abstract.

Created with p5js using multiple shape primitives, gradient noise and various sine & cosine functions.

The algorithm contains multiple loops plotting several thousands of shapes and lines and may take up to 12 seconds to display the artwork.

Dutch action 10-8-6-4 at 10 minute intervals.

metadata.name: Soil Horizon Square #12
metadata.description:
A square version of the previous release of Soil Horizon. 

A Soil horizon is a layer parallel to the soil surface whose physical, chemical, and biological characteristics differ from the layers above and beneath.

Horizons are defined in many cases by obvious physical features, mainly color and texture.

Available for the Soil Horizon holders only.
2000x2000
Coded with p5js by @LESSLIE
___

Click the Open Live button
Press [S] to save the high-resolution version

May 2022

metadata.name: Chaotic Growth #35
metadata.description:
Chaotic growth is based on a modified version of the differential line algorithm by Anders Hoff [1]. This algorithm uses an attraction-repulsion-model to imitate growth on a connected set of nodes. 

In this piece I explored an adaption of this algorithm attempting to visualize systems growing past their point of sustainability, creating new dynamics and eventually spiraling out of control. Some iterations may grow smoothly for some time but will quickly turn into a chaotic system of unsustainable growth. The smooth and organic shape of growth in the beginning is contrasted by the spikey, incoherent offshoots. 


Created in Vanilla JS.

Controls:
S - Save image
Space - Pause/Unpause


Best viewed in Chrome. Different browsers may produce slightly different outputs.

[1] https://inconvergent.net/generative/differential-line/

metadata.name: Flower Arrangement #72
metadata.description:
Flower arrangement made by code.

Possible features:
- Style: Natural, Oval, Triangular, Grassy
- Orientation: Square, Portrait, Landscape
- Palette: White, Cream, Tan, Pink, Green, Blue, Yellow, Orange
- Primary flower: Mix, Gerbera, Gerbera 2, Dahlia, Dahlia 2, Spiky, Unknown
- Primary color: Random, Light, Dark
- Secondary color: Random, Light, Dark
- Vase shape: Cylinder, Tumbler, Round, Curve
- Dish: true, false
- Table: true, false
- Texture: true, false

Live view options:
- Press "s" key: Saves the high resolution image (3300 x 3300 for square, 4200 x 3300 for portrait, 3300 x 4200 for landscape)

Depending on the device you run it on, it may take some time for the drawing to complete.
Best viewed in larger window size.
Made with p5js.

August 2022
